n</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mn>2</mn> <mi>x</mi> </math></span> and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{sec}}\\,2x\"> <mrow> <mtext>sec</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mn>2</mn> <mi>x</mi> </math></span> in terms of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{tan}}\\,x\"> <mrow> <mtext>tan</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mi>x</mi> </math></span>.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13195","referenceCode":"19M.1.AHL.TZ1.H_9b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that sec 2 x + tan 2 x = cos x + sin x cos x − sin x .","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.15—Further derivatives and indefinite integration of these, partial fractions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.10—Compound angle identities"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}